# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tilemap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:tilemap/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] In computer graphics, a **heightmap** or **heightfield** is a raster image used mainly as Discrete Global Grid in secondary elevation modeling.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Each pixel stores values, such as surface elevation data, for display in 3D computer graphics.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] A heightmap can be used in bump mapping to calculate where this 3D data would create shadow in a material, in displacement mapping to displace the actual geometric position of points over the textured surface, or for terrain where the heightmap is converted into a 3D mesh.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] A heightmap contains one channel interpreted as a distance of displacement or "height" from the "floor" of a surface and sometimes visualized as luma of a grayscale image, with black representing minimum height and white representing maximum height.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] When the map is rendered, the designer can specify the amount of displacement for each unit of the height channel, which corresponds to the “contrast” of the image.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmaps can be stored by themselves in existing grayscale image formats, with or without specialized metadata, or in specialized file formats such as Daylon Leveller, GenesisIV and Terragen documents.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] One may also exploit the use of individual color channels to increase detail.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] For example, a standard RGB 8-bit image can only show 256 values of grey and hence only 256 heights.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] By using colors, a greater number of heights can be stored (for a 24-bit image, 2563 = 16,777,216 heights can be represented (2564 = 4,294,967,296 if the alpha channel is also used)).
[src:tilemap/heightmap] This technique is especially useful where height varies slightly over a large area.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Using only grey values, because the heights must be mapped to only 256 values, the rendered terrain appears flat, with "steps" in certain places.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmaps are commonly used in geographic information systems, where they are called digital elevation models.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmaps can be created by hand with a classical paint program or a special terrain editor.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] These editors visualize the terrain in 3D and allow the user to modify the surface.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Normally there are tools to raise, lower, smooth or erode the terrain.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Another way to create a terrain is to use a terrain generation algorithm.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] This can be for example a 2D simplex noise function or by diffusion-limited aggregation.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Another method is to reconstruct heightmaps from real world data, for example using synthetic aperture radar.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmaps are widely used in terrain rendering software and modern video games.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmaps are an ideal way to store digital terrain elevations; compared to a regular polygonal mesh, they require substantially less memory for a given level of detail.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Most modern 3D computer modelling programs are capable of using data from heightmaps in the form of bump, normal, or displacement maps to quickly and precisely create complex terrain and other surfaces.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] In the earliest games using software rendering, the elements often represented heights of columns of voxels rendered with ray casting.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] In most newer games, the elements represent the height coordinate of polygons in a mesh.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Although the terms heightmap and heightfield are often indistinguishable from each other, there is still a small difference in the terms.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmap comes from the mathematical term 'map' and heightfield comes from the mathematical term 'vector field'.
[src:tilemap/heightmap] Heightmap is the more correct description because most heightfields are not a (vector) field in mathematical terms but they are always a map (in mathematical terms as well as in the visual representation).
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Once common, isometric projection became less so with the advent of more powerful 3D graphics systems, and as video games began to focus more on action and individual characters.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] However, video games using isometric projection—especially computer role-playing games—saw a resurgence in the 2010s within the indie gaming scene.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Corresponding 3D camera rotation angles for true isometric projection (at left) and the form of dimetric projection commonly found in video games and pixel art (at right).
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] axes, as well as the equal lengths of each of the cube's edges.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] is equal to 30° and forms a pixel ratio of ≈1.732:1.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The form of dimetric projection commonly used in video games and pixel art.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] axes are the same, and only some of the lengths of the cube's edges are equal.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] is equal to ≈26.565° and forms a 2:1 pixel ratio.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In video game development and pixel art, the technique has become popular because of the ease with which 2D sprite- and tile-based graphics can be made to represent 3D gaming environments.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Because parallel projected objects do not change in size as they move about an area, there is no need for the computer to scale sprites or do the complex calculations necessary to simulate visual perspective.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] This allowed 8-bit and 16-bit game systems (and, more recently, handheld and mobile systems) to portray large game areas quickly and easily.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] And, while the depth confusion problems of parallel projection can sometimes be a problem, good game and level design can alleviate this.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Though not limited strictly to isometric video game graphics, pre-rendered 2D graphics can possess a higher fidelity and use more advanced graphical techniques than may be possible on commonly available computer hardware, even with 3D hardware acceleration.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Similarly to modern CGI used in motion pictures, graphics can be rendered once on a powerful super computer or render farm, and then displayed many times on less powerful consumer hardware, such as on television sets, tablet computers and smartphones.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] This means that static pre-rendered isometric graphics often look better compared to their contemporary real-time-rendered counterparts, and may age better over time compared to their peers.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] However, this advantage may be less pronounced today than it was in the past, as developments in graphical technology equalize or produce diminishing returns, and current levels of graphical fidelity become "good enough" for many people.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] There are also gameplay advantages to using an isometric or near-isometric perspective in video games.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] For instance, compared to a purely top-down game, they add a third dimension, opening up new avenues for aiming and platforming.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Compared to a first- or third-person video game, they allow a player to more easily field and control a large number of units, such as a full party of characters in a computer role-playing game, or an army of minions in a real-time strategy game.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Further, they may alleviate situations where a player may become distracted from a game's core mechanics by having to constantly manage an unwieldy 3D camera.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] I.e., the player can focus on playing the game itself, and not on manipulating the game's camera.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In the present day, rather than being purely a source of nostalgia, the revival of isometric projection is the result of tangible design benefits.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Some disadvantages of pre-rendered isometric graphics are that, as display resolutions and display aspect ratios continue to evolve, static 2D images need to be re-rendered each time in order to keep pace, or potentially suffer from the effects of pixelation and require anti-aliasing.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Re-rendering a game's graphics is not always possible, however; as was the case in 2012, when Beamdog remade BioWare's *Baldur's Gate* (1998).
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Beamdog were lacking the original developers' creative art assets (the original data was lost in a flood) and opted for simple 2D graphics scaling with "smoothing", without re-rendering the game's sprites.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The results were a certain "fuzziness", or lack of "crispness", compared to the original game's graphics.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] This does not affect real-time rendered polygonal isometric video games, however, as changing their display resolutions or aspect ratios is trivial, in comparison.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The projection commonly used in video games deviates slightly from "true" isometric due to the limitations of raster graphics.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Lines in the x and y directions would not follow a neat pixel pattern if drawn in the required 30° to the horizontal.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] While modern computers can eliminate this problem using anti-aliasing, earlier computer graphics did not support enough colors or possess enough CPU power to accomplish this.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Instead, a 2:1 pixel pattern ratio would be used to draw the x and y axis lines, resulting in these axes following a ≈26.565° (arctan(1/2)) angle to the horizontal.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Some three-dimensional games were released as early as the 1970s, but the first video games to use the distinct visual style of isometric projection in the meaning described above were arcade games in the early 1980s.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The use of isometric graphics in video games began with Data East's arcade game *Treasure Island*, released in Japan in September 1981, but it was not released internationally until June 1982.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The first isometric game to be released internationally was Sega's *Zaxxon*, which was significantly more popular and influential; it was released in Japan in December 1981 and internationally in April 1982.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] *Zaxxon* is an isometric shooter where the player flies a space plane through scrolling levels.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] It is also one of the first video games to display shadows.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Another early isometric game is *Q*bert*.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Warren Davis and Jeff Lee began programming the concept around April 1982.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The game's production began in the summer and then released in October or November 1982.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] *Q*bert* shows a static pyramid in an isometric perspective, with the player controlling a character which can jump around on the pyramid.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In February 1983, the isometric platform arcade game *Congo Bongo* was released, running on the same hardware as *Zaxxon*.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] It allows the player character to traverse non-scrolling isometric levels, including three-dimensional climbing and falling.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The same is possible in the arcade title *Marble Madness*, released in 1984.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In 1983, isometric games were no longer exclusive to the arcade market and also entered home computers, with the release of *Blue Max* for the Atari 8-bit computers and *Ant Attack* for the ZX Spectrum.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In *Ant Attack*, the player can move forward in any direction of the scrolling game, offering complete free movement rather than fixed to one axis as with *Zaxxon*.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The views can also be changed around a 90 degrees axis.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The ZX Spectrum magazine, *Crash*, consequently awarded it 100% in the graphics category for this new technique, known as "Soft Solid 3-D".
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] A year later, the ZX Spectrum game *Knight Lore* was released.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] It was generally regarded as a revolutionary title that defined the subsequent genre of isometric adventure games.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Following *Knight Lore*, many isometric titles were seen on home computers – to an extent that it once was regarded as being the second most cloned piece of software after *WordStar*, according to researcher Jan Krikke.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Other examples out of those were *Highway Encounter* (1985), *Batman* (1986), *Head Over Heels* (1987) and *La Abadía del Crimen* (1987).
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Isometric perspective was not limited to action and adventure games.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] For example, the 1989 strategy game *Populous* uses isometric perspective.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] But with the advent of 3D acceleration on personal computers and gaming consoles, games previously using a 2D perspective generally started switching to true 3D (and perspective projection) instead.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Also during the 1990s, isometric graphics began being used for Japanese role-playing video games (JRPGs) on console systems, particularly tactical role-playing games, many of which still use isometric graphics today.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Examples include *Front Mission* (1995), *Tactics Ogre* (1995) and *Final Fantasy Tactics* (1997)—the latter of which used 3D graphics to create an environment where the player could freely rotate the camera.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Other titles such as *Vandal Hearts* (1996) and *Breath of Fire III* (1997) carefully emulated an isometric or parallel view, but actually used perspective projection.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Isometric, or similar, perspectives become popular in role-playing video games, such as *Fallout* and *Baldur's Gate*.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In some cases, these role-playing games became defined by their isometric perspective, which allows larger scale battles.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Isometric projection has seen continued relevance in the new millennium with the release of several newly-crowdfunded role-playing games on Kickstarter.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] These include the *Shadowrun Returns* series (2013–2015) by Harebrained Schemes; the *Pillars of Eternity* series (2015–2018) and *Tyranny* (2016) by Obsidian Entertainment; and *Torment: Tides of Numenera* (2017) by inXile Entertainment.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Both Obsidian Entertainment and inXile Entertainment have employed, or were founded by, former members of Black Isle Studios and Interplay Entertainment.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Obsidian Entertainment in particular wanted to "bring back the look and feel of the Infinity Engine games like *Baldur's Gate*, *Icewind Dale*, and *Planescape: Torment*".
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Lastly, several pseudo-isometric 3D RPGs, such as *Divinity: Original Sin* (2014), *Wasteland 2* (2014) and *Dead State* (2014), have been crowdfunded using Kickstarter.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] These titles differ from the above games, however, in that they use *perspective projection* instead of *parallel projection*.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The term "isometric perspective" is frequently misapplied to any game with an angled, overhead view.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Also, not all "isometric" video games rely solely on pre-rendered 2D sprites.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] One advantage of top-down *oblique projection* over other near-isometric perspectives, is that objects fit more snugly within non-overlapping square graphical tiles, thereby potentially eliminating the need for an additional Z-order in calculations, and requiring fewer pixels.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] One of the most common problems with programming games that use isometric (or more likely dimetric) projections is the ability to map between events that happen on the 2D plane of the screen and the actual location in the isometric space, called world space.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] A common example is picking the tile that lies right under the cursor when a user clicks.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] One such method is using the same rotation matrices that originally produced the isometric view in reverse to turn a point in screen coordinates into a point that would lie on the game board surface before it was rotated.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Then, the world x and y values can be calculated by dividing by the tile width and height.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Another way that is less computationally intensive and can have good results if the method is called on every frame, rests on the assumption that a square board was rotated by 45 degrees and then squashed to be half its original height.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] A virtual grid is overlaid on the projection as shown on the diagram, with axes virtual-x and virtual-y.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Clicking any tile on the central axis of the board where (x, y) = (tileMapWidth / 2, y), will produce the same tile value for both world-x and world-y which in this example is 3 (0 indexed).
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Selecting the tile that lies one position on the right on the virtual grid, actually moves one tile less on the world-y and one tile more on the world-x.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] This is the formula that calculates world-x by taking the virtual-y and adding the virtual-x from the center of the board.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] Likewise world-y is calculated by taking virtual-y and subtracting virtual-x.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] These calculations measure from the central axis, as shown, so the results must be translated by half the board.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] This method might seem counter intuitive at first since the coordinates of a virtual grid are taken, rather than the original isometric world, and there is no one-to-one correspondence between virtual tiles and isometric tiles.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] A tile on the grid will contain more than one isometric tile, and depending on where it is clicked it should map to different coordinates.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] The key in this method is that the virtual coordinates are floating point numbers rather than integers.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] A virtual-x and y value can be (3.5, 3.5) which means the center of the third tile.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] In the diagram on the left, this falls in the third tile on the y in detail.
[src:tilemap/isometric-video-game-graphics] When the virtual-x and y must add up to 4, the world x will also be 4.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Parallax scrolling was popularized in 2D computer graphics with its introduction to video games in the early 1980s.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Some parallax scrolling was used in the arcade video game *Jump Bug* (1981).
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] It used a limited form of parallax scrolling with the main scene scrolling while the starry night sky is fixed and clouds move slowly, adding depth to the scenery.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The following year, *Moon Patrol* (1982) implemented a full form of parallax scrolling, with three separate background layers scrolling at different speeds, simulating the distance between them.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] *Moon Patrol* is often credited with popularizing parallax scrolling.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] *Jungle King* (1982), later called *Jungle Hunt*, also had parallax scrolling, and was released a month after *Moon Patrol* in June 1982.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] There are four main methods of parallax scrolling used in titles for arcade system board, video game console and personal computer systems.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Some display systems support multiple background layers that can be scrolled independently in horizontal and vertical directions and composited on one another, simulating a multiplane camera.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] On such a display system, a game can produce parallax by simply changing each layer's position by a different amount in the same direction.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Layers that move more quickly are perceived to be closer to the virtual camera.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Layers can be placed in front of the *playfield*—the layer containing the objects with which the player interacts—for various reasons such as to provide increased dimension, obscure some of the action of the game, or distract the player.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Programmers may also make pseudo-layers of sprites—individually controllable moving objects drawn by hardware on top of or behind the layers—if they are available on the display system.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] For instance *Star Force*, an overhead-view vertically scrolling shooter for NES, used this for its starfield, and *Final Fight* for the Super NES used this technique for the layer immediately in front of the main playfield.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The Amiga computer has sprites which can have any height and can be set horizontal with the copper co-processor, which makes them ideal for this purpose.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Risky Woods on the Amiga uses sprites multiplexed with the copper to create an entire fullscreen parallax background layer as an alternative to the system's dual playfield mode.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Scrolling displays built up of individual tiles can be made to 'float' over a repeating background layer by animating the individual tiles' bitmaps in order to portray the parallax effect.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Color cycling can be used to animate tiles quickly on the whole screen.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] This software effect gives the illusion of another (hardware) layer.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Many games used this technique for a scrolling star-field, but sometimes a more intricate or multi-directional effect is achieved, such as in the game *Parallax* by Sensible Software.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] In raster graphics, the lines of pixels in an image are typically composited and refreshed in top-to-bottom order with a slight delay (called the horizontal blanking interval) between drawing one line and drawing the next line.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Games designed for older graphical chipsets—such as those of the third and fourth generations of video game consoles, those of dedicated TV games, or those of similar handheld systems—take advantage of the raster characteristics to create the illusion of more layers.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Some display systems have only one layer.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] These include most of the classic 8-bit systems (such as the Commodore 64, Nintendo Entertainment System, Master System, PC Engine/TurboGrafx-16 and original Game Boy).
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The more sophisticated games on such systems generally divide the layer into horizontal strips, each with a different position and rate of scrolling.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Typically, strips higher on the screen will represent things farther away from the virtual camera or one strip will be held stationary to display status information.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The program will then wait for horizontal blank and change the layer's scroll position just before the display system begins to draw each scanline.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] This is called a "raster effect" and is also useful for changing the system palette to provide a gradient background.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Some platforms (such as the Commodore 64, Amiga, Master System, PC Engine/TurboGrafx-16, Sega Mega Drive/Genesis, Super NES, Game Boy, Game Boy Advance and Nintendo DS) provide a horizontal blank interrupt for automatically setting the registers independently of the rest of the program.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Others, such as the NES, require the use of cycle-timed code, which is specially written to take exactly as long to execute as the video chip takes to draw one scanline, or timers inside game cartridges that generate interrupts after a given number of scanlines have been drawn.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Many NES games use this technique to draw their status bars, and *Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles II: The Arcade Game* and *Vice: Project Doom* for NES use it to scroll background layers at different rates.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] More advanced raster techniques can produce interesting effects.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] A system can achieve a very effective depth of field if layers with rasters are combined; *Sonic the Hedgehog*, *Sonic The Hedgehog 2*, *ActRaiser*, *Lionheart*, *Kid Chaos* and *Street Fighter II* used this effect well.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] If each scanline has its own layer, the *Pole Position* effect is produced, which creates a pseudo-3D road (or a pseudo-3D ball court as in *NBA Jam*) on a 2D system.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] If the display system supports rotation and scaling in addition to scrolling—an effect popularly known as Mode 7—changing the rotation and scaling factors can draw a projection of a plane (as in *F-Zero* and *Super Mario Kart*) or can warp the playfield to create an extra challenge factor.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Another advanced technique is row/column scrolling, where rows/columns of tiles on a screen can be scrolled individually.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] This technique is implemented in the graphics chips of various Sega arcade system boards since the Sega Space Harrier and System 16, the Sega Mega Drive/Genesis console, and the Capcom CP System, Irem M-92 and Taito F3 System arcade game boards.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] In the following animation, three layers are moving leftward at different speeds.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Their speeds decrease from front to back and correspond to increases in relative distance from the viewer.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The ground layer is moving 8 times as fast as the vegetation layer.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] The vegetation layer is moving two times as fast as the cloud layer.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] One of the first implementations of parallax scrolling in the browser was created and shared in a blog post by web developer Glutnix in 2007, this included example code and a demo using JavaScript and CSS 2 that supported Internet Explorer 6 and other browsers of that era.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] In a February 2008 tutorial on web design blog Think Vitamin, web designer Paul Annett explained how he had created a parallax effect using CSS and without JavaScript for the website of Silverback, a usability testing app.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] He demonstrated the effect on stage at SXSW Interactive 2009, with the help of audience participation and a man in a gorilla suit.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Advocates argue it is a simple way to embrace the fluidity of the Web, citing the Silverback website as the first example they had come across.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] Proponents use parallax backgrounds as a tool to better engage users and improve the overall experience that a website provides.
[src:tilemap/parallax-scrolling] However, a Purdue University study, published in 2013, revealed the following findings: "... although parallax scrolling enhanced certain aspects of the user experience, it did not necessarily improve the overall user experience".
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In computer displays, filmmaking, television production, video games and other kinetic displays, **scrolling** is sliding text, images or video across a monitor or display, vertically or horizontally.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] "Scrolling," as such, does not change the layout of the text or pictures but moves (pans or tilts) the user's view across what is apparently a larger image that is not wholly seen.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] A common television and movie special effect is to scroll credits, while leaving the background stationary.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling may take place completely without user intervention (as in film credits) or, on an interactive device, be triggered by touchscreen or a keypress and continue without further intervention until a further user action, or be entirely controlled by input devices.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling may take place in discrete increments (perhaps one or a few lines of text at a time), or continuously (**smooth scrolling**).
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Frame rate is the speed at which an entire image is redisplayed.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] It is related to scrolling in that changes to text and image position can only happen as often as the image can be redisplayed.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] When frame rate is a limiting factor, one smooth scrolling technique is to blur images during movement that would otherwise appear to "jump".
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling is often carried out on a computer by the CPU (*software scrolling*) or by a graphics processor.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Some systems feature *hardware scrolling*, where an image may be offset as it is displayed, without any frame buffer manipulation (see also hardware windowing).
[src:tilemap/scrolling] This was especially common in 8 and 16bit video game consoles.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In a WIMP-style graphical user interface (GUI), user-controlled scrolling is carried out by manipulating a scrollbar with a mouse, or using keyboard shortcuts, often the arrow keys.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling is often supported by text user interfaces and command line interfaces.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Older computer terminals changed the entire contents of the display one screenful ("page") at a time; this paging mode requires fewer resources than scrolling.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling displays often also support page mode.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Typically certain keys or key combinations page up or down; on PC-compatible keyboards the page up and page down keys or the space bar are used; earlier computers often used control key combinations.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Some computer mice have a scroll wheel, which scrolls the display, often vertically, when rolled; others have scroll balls or tilt wheels which allow both vertical and horizontal scrolling.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Some software supports other ways of scrolling.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Adobe Reader has a mode identified by a small hand icon ("hand tool") on the document, which can then be dragged by clicking on it and moving the mouse as if sliding a large sheet of paper.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] When this feature is implemented on a touchscreen it is called *kinetic scrolling*.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Touch-screens often use *inertial scrolling*, in which the scrolling motion of an object continues in a decaying fashion after release of the touch, simulating the appearance of an object with inertia.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] An early implementation of such behavior was in the "Star7" PDA of Sun Microsystems ca.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling can be controlled in other software-dependent ways by a PC mouse.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Some scroll wheels can be pressed down, functioning like a button.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Depending on the software, this allows both horizontal and vertical scrolling by dragging in the direction desired; when the mouse is moved to the original position, scrolling stops.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] A few scroll wheels can also be tilted, scrolling horizontally in one direction until released.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] On touchscreen devices, scrolling is a multi-touch gesture, done by swiping a finger on the screen vertically in the direction opposite to where the user wants to scroll to.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] If any content is too wide to fit on a display, horizontal scrolling is required to view all of it.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In applications such as graphics and spreadsheets there is often more content than can fit either the width or the height of the screen at a comfortable scale, and scrolling in both directions is necessary.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In contrast to material divided into discrete pages, the web design approach of infinite scrolling dynamically adds new material to the user display, leading to a continuous, apparently bottomless or endless scrolling experience.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In languages written horizontally, such as most Western languages, text documents longer than will fit on the screen are often displayed wrapped and sized to fit the screen width, and scrolled vertically to bring desired content into view.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] It is possible to display lines too long to fit the display without wrapping, scrolling horizontally to view each entire line.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] However, this requires inconvenient constant line-by-line scrolling, while vertical scrolling is only needed after reading a full screenful.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Software such as word processors and web browsers normally uses word-wrapping to display as many words in a single line as will fit the width of the screen or window or, for text organised in columns, each column.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling texts, also referred to as *scrolltexts* or *scrollers*, played an important part in the birth of the computer demo culture.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] The software crackers often used their deep knowledge of computer platforms to transform the information that accompanied their releases into crack intros.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] The sole role of these intros was to scroll the text on the screen in an impressive way.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling is commonly used to display the credits at the end of films and television programs.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Scrolling is often used in the form of a news ticker towards the bottom of the picture for content such as television news, scrolling sideways across the screen, delivering short-form content.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In the dynamic layout of kinetic typography, scrolling typography can scroll across the flat screen, or can appear to recede or advance.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] An iconic example is the *Star Wars* opening crawl inspired by the Flash Gordon serials.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] In computer and video games, scrolling of a playing field allows the player to control an object in a large contiguous area.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Early examples of this method include Taito's 1974 vertical-scrolling racing video game *Speed Race*, Sega's 1976 forward-scrolling racing games *Moto-Cross* (*Fonz*) and *Road Race*, and *Super Bug*.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Previously the flip-screen method was used to indicate moving backgrounds.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Parallax scrolling, which was first featured in *Moon Patrol*, involves several semi-transparent layers (called playfields), which scroll on top of each other at varying rates in order to give an early pseudo-3D illusion of depth.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] A 1993 article by George Fitzmaurice studied spatially aware palmtop computers.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] These devices had a 3D sensor, and moving the device caused the contents to move as if the contents were fixed in place.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] This interaction could be referred to as “moving to scroll.” Also, if the user moved the device away from their body, they would zoom in; conversely, the device would zoom out if the user pulled the device closer to them.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Smartphone cameras and “optical flow” image analysis utilize this technique nowadays.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] A 1996 research paper by Jun Rekimoto analyzed tilting operations as scrolling techniques on small screen interfaces.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] Users could not only tilt to scroll, but also tilt to select menu items.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] These techniques proved especially useful for field workers, since they only needed to hold and control the device with one hand.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] A study from 2013 by Selina Sharmin, Oleg Špakov, and Kari-Jouko Räihä explored the action of reading text on a screen while the text auto-scrolls based on the user's eye tracking patterns.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] The control group simply read text on a screen and manually scrolled.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] The study found that participants preferred to read primarily at the top of the screen, so the screen scrolled down whenever participants’ eyes began to look toward the bottom of the screen.
[src:tilemap/scrolling] This auto-scrolling caused no statistically significant difference in reading speed or performance.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] A **tile-based video game**, or **grid-based video game**, is a type of video game where the playing area consists of small square (or, much less often, rectangular, parallelogram, or hexagonal) graphic images referred to as *tiles* laid out in a grid.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] That the screen is made of such tiles is a technical distinction, and may not be obvious to people playing the game.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The complete set of tiles available for use in a playing area is called a *tileset*.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Tile-based games usually simulate a top-down, side view, or 2.5D view of the playing area, and are almost always two-dimensional.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Much video game hardware from the late 1970s through the mid-1990s has native support for displaying tiled screens with little interaction from the CPU.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Tile-based games are not a distinct video game genre.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The term refers to the technology that the hardware or game engine uses for its visual representation.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] For example, *Pac-Man* is an action game, *Ultima* is a role-playing video game and *Civilization* is a turn-based strategy game, but all three render the world as tiles.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] *Ultima III* and *Civilization* draw the tiles via software, while the maze in the original arcade version of *Pac-Man* is made of tiles displayed by the game's graphics hardware.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Tiles allow developers to build with a set of reusable components instead of drawing everything individually.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Tile-based video games usually use a texture atlas for performance reasons.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] They also store metadata about the tiles, such as collision, damage, and entities, either with a 2-dimensional array mapping the tiles, or a second texture atlas mirroring the visual one but coding metadata by colour.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] This approach allows for simple, visual map data, letting level designers create entire worlds with a tile reference sheet and perhaps a text editor, a paint program, or a simple level editor (many older games included the editor in the game).
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Examples of tile-based game engine/IDEs include RPG Maker, Game Maker, Construct, and Godot.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Variations include level data using "material tiles" that are procedurally transformed into the final tile graphics, and groupings of tiles as larger-scale "supertiles" or "chunks," allowing large tiled worlds to be constructed under heavy memory constraints.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Ultima 7 uses a "tile," "chunk" and "superchunk" three-layer system to construct an enormous, detailed world within the PCs of the early 1990s.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The tile-map model was introduced to video games by Namco's arcade game *Galaxian* (1979), which ran on the Namco Galaxian arcade system board, capable of displaying multiple colors per tile as well as scrolling.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] It used a tile size of 8×8 pixels, which since became the most common tile size used in video games.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Some video game consoles such as the Intellivision, released in 1979, were designed to use tile-based graphics, since their games had to fit into video game cartridges as small as 4K in size.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Home computers had hardware tile support in the form of ASCII characters arranged in a grid, usually for the purposes of displaying text, but games could be written using letters and punctuation as game elements.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The Atari 400/800 home computers, released in 1979, allow the standard character set to be replaced by a custom one.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The new characters don't have to be glyphs, but the walls of a maze or ladders or any game graphics that fit in an 8x8 pixel square.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The video coprocessor provides different modes for displaying character grids.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] In most modes, individual monochrome characters can be displayed in one of four colors; others allow characters to be constructed of 2-bit pixels instead, which allowed up to 5 colors to be displayed by swapping between 2 colors via an extra bit in the tile index byte.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Atari used the term *redefined characters* and not *tiles*.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Most early tile-based games used a top-down perspective.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] The top-down perspective evolved to a simulated 45-degree angle, seen in 1994's *Final Fantasy VI*, allowing the player to see both the top and one side of objects, to give more sense of depth; this style dominated 8-bit and 16-bit console role-playing games.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Ultimate Play the Game developed a series of video games in the 1980s that employed a tile-based isometric perspective.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] As computers advanced, isometric and dimetric perspectives began to predominate in tile-based games, using parallelogram-shaped tiles instead of square tiles.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Hexagonal tile-based games have been limited for the most part to the strategy and wargaming genres.
[src:tilemap/tile-based-video-game] Notable examples include the Sega Genesis game *Master of Monsters*, SSI's *Five Star* series of wargames starting with *Panzer General*, the *Age of Wonders* series and *Battle for Wesnoth*.
